      "\n- The specific goal at the point of error is to prove `False` given a set of hypotheses:\n    - `Rxy : x ≺ y` (x is related to y)\n    - `hy₁ : y ⊧ φ` (φ is true at y)\n    - `hy₂ : y ⊭ ψ` (ψ is false at y)\n    - `Rxz : x ≺ z` (x is related to z)\n    - `hz₁ : z ⊧ ψ` (ψ is true at z)\n    - `hz₂ : z ⊭ φ` (φ is false at z)\n    - `Rzy : z ≺ y` (z is related to y)\n\nThe proof attempts to derive a contradiction from these hypotheses. The strategy is to use the piecewise connectedness of `F` to show that `x`, `y`, and `z` must form a cycle in the relation `≺`, which would then contradict the fact that `φ` and `ψ` have opposite truth values at `y` and `z`.\n\nLooking at the hypotheses, we have `x ≺ y`, `x ≺ z`, and `z ≺ y`. This forms a cycle: `x ≺ z`, `z ≺ y`, and `y` is related back to `x` via the original `Rxy : x ≺ y`. In a piecewise connected space, this cycle must be part of a strongly connected component.\n\nHowever, the hypotheses also give us:\n- At `y`: `φ` is true and `ψ` is false\n- At `z`: `ψ` is true and `φ` is false\n\nThis means that `φ` and `ψ` have opposite truth values at `y` and `z`, which are related by `z ≺ y`. In a Kripke model, if `w ≺ v`, then all formulas true at `w` must also be true at `v`. This is the \"hereditary\" property of Kripke models.\n\nSo, since `z ≺ y`:\n- If `φ` is true at `z`, it must be true at `y`. But we know `φ` is false at `y` from `hy₂`. This is a contradiction.\n- If `ψ` is true at `y`, it must be true at `z`. But we know `ψ` is false at `z` from `hz₂`. This is also a contradiction.\n\nSo the hypotheses are indeed contradictory, and the goal `⊢ False` is correct. The issue is that the proof attempt is incomplete (it ends with `sorry`).\n\nTo fix this, we need to apply the hereditary property correctly. The key insight is that `z ≺ y` implies that the truth values at `z` must be a subset of the truth values at `y`. But we have `φ` false at `y` and true at `z`, and `ψ` true at `y` and false at `z`. This violates the hereditary property.\n\nLet's write the proof:\n\n```tactics\nimport Foundation.Propositional.Kripke2.Basic\nimport Foundation.Propositional.Entailment.LC\nimport Foundation.Vorspiel.Rel.Convergent\nimport Foundation.Vorspiel.Rel.Euclidean\nimport Foundation.Vorspiel.Rel.Coreflexive\nimport Foundation.Vorspiel.Rel.Connected\n\nnamespace LO.Propositional\n\nnamespace Axioms\n\nvariable {F : Type*} [LogicalConnective F]\nvariable (φ ψ χ : F)\n\nprotected alias PCon₁ := LO.Axioms.Dummett\n\nprotected abbrev PCon₂ := (φ ➝ ψ) ➝ ((φ ➝ ψ) ➝ φ)\n\nprotected abbrev PCon₃ := (φ ➝ ψ) ➝ ((φ ➝ ψ) ➝ ψ)\n\nprotected abbrev PCon₄ := (φ ➝ ψ ⋎ χ) ➝ (φ ➝ ψ) ⋎ (φ ➝ χ)\n\nprotected abbrev PCon₅ := (φ ⋏ ψ ⋎ χ) ➝ (φ ➝ χ) ⋎ (φ ➝ ψ)\n\nprotected abbrev PCon₆ := ((φ ➝ ψ) ➝ ψ) ⋏ ((ψ ➝ φ) ➝ φ) ➝ (φ ⋎ ψ)\n\nend Axioms\n\n\nopen Kripke2\nopen Formula.Kripke2\n\nnamespace Kripke2\n\nvariable {F : Kripke2.Frame} {φ ψ : Formula ℕ}\n\nnamespace Frame\n\nprotected abbrev IsPiecewiseConnected (F : Kripke2.Frame) := _root_.IsPiecewiseConnected F.Rel\n@[grind →] lemma p_connected  [F.IsPiecewiseConnected] : ∀ {x y z : F}, x ≺ y → x ≺ z → y ≺ z ∨ y = z ∨ z ≺ y := by apply IsPiecewiseConnected.p_connected\n@[grind →] lemma p_connected' [F.IsPiecewiseConnected] : ∀ {x y z : F}, x ≺ y → x ≺ z → y ≠ z → y ≺ z ∨ z ≺ y := by apply IsPiecewiseConnected.p_connected'\n\nend Frame\n\n-- TODO: need formula level hereditary\n@[simp high, grind .]\nlemma valid_axiomSym_of_isSymmetric [F.IsPiecewiseConnected] : F ⊧ Axioms.PCon₁ φ ψ := by\n  intro V x;\n  by_contra hC;\n  rcases Satisfies.not_def_or.mp hC with ⟨h₁, h₂⟩; clear hC;\n  obtain ⟨y, Rxy, hy₁, hy₂⟩ := Satisfies.not_def_imp.mp h₁; clear h₁;\n  obtain ⟨z, Rxz, hz₁, hz₂⟩ := Satisfies.not_def_imp.mp h₂; clear h₂;\n  rcases F.p_connected Rxy Rxz with Ryz | rfl | Rzy;\n  . sorry;\n  . tauto;\n  . sorry;\n```\n\nNow we need to fix the last `sorry`. The state before the `sorry` is:\n- `Rxy : x ≺ y`\n- `hy₁ : y ⊧ φ`\n- `hy₂ : y ⊭ ψ`\n- `Rxz : x ≺ z`\n- `hz₁ : z ⊧ ψ`\n- `hz₂ : z ⊭ φ`\n- `Rzy : z ≺ y`\n- Goal: `⊢ False`\n\nThe strategy is to use the hereditary property. `z ≺ y` implies that the truth values at `z` must be a subset of the truth values at `y`.\nHowever, we have:\n- `hz₁ : z ⊧ ψ` (ψ is true at z)\n- `hy₂ : y ⊭ ψ` (ψ is false at y)\n- `hz₂ : z ⊭ φ` (φ is false at z)\n- `hy₁ : y ⊧ φ` (φ is true at y)\n\nThis violates the hereditary property because `z ≺ y` should imply that if `φ` is true at `y`, it's also true at `z`, and if `ψ` is true at `y`, it's also true at `z`. But we have `φ` true at `y` and false at `z`, and `ψ` false at `y` and true at `z`.\n\nSo we can derive a contradiction from these facts. Let's apply the hereditary property:\n\n```tactics\nimport Foundation.Propositional.Kripke2.Basic\nimport Foundation.Propositional.Entailment.LC\nimport Foundation.Vorspiel.Rel.Convergent\nimport Foundation.Vorspiel.Rel.Euclidean\nimport Foundation.Vorspiel.Rel.Coreflexive\nimport Foundation.Vorspiel.Rel.Connected\n\nnamespace LO.Propositional\n\nnamespace Axioms\n\nvariable {F : Type*} [LogicalConnective F]\nvariable (φ ψ χ : F)\n\nprotected alias PCon₁ := LO.Axioms.Dummett\n\nprotected abbrev PCon₂ := (φ ➝ ψ) ➝ ((φ ➝ ψ) ➝ φ)\n\nprotected abbrev PCon₃ := (φ ➝ ψ) ➝ ((φ ➝ ψ) ➝ ψ)\n\nprotected abbrev PCon₄ := (φ ➝ ψ ⋎ χ) ➝ (φ ➝ ψ) ⋎ (φ ➝ χ)\n\nprotected abbrev PCon₅ := (φ ⋏ ψ ⋎ χ) ➝ (φ ➝ χ) ⋎ (φ ➝ ψ)\n\nprotected abbrev PCon₆ := ((φ ➝ ψ) ➝ ψ) ⋏ ((ψ ➝ φ) ➝ φ) ➝ (φ ⋎ ψ)\n\nend Axioms\n\n\nopen Kripke2\nopen Formula.Kripke2\n\nnamespace Kripke2\n\nvariable {F : Kripke2.Frame} {φ ψ : Formula ℕ}\n\nnamespace Frame\n\nprotected abbrev IsPiecewiseConnected (F : Kripke2.Frame) := _root_.IsPiecewiseConnected F.Rel\n@[grind →] lemma p_connected  [F.IsPiecewiseConnected] : ∀ {x y z : F}, x ≺ y → x ≺ z → y ≺ z ∨ y = z ∨ z ≺ y := by apply IsPiecewiseConnected.p_connected\n@[grind →] lemma p_connected' [F.IsPiecewiseConnected] : ∀ {x y z : F}, x ≺ y → x ≺ z → y ≠ z → y ≺ z ∨ z ≺ y := by apply IsPiecewiseConnected.p_connected'\n\nend